<br>
The United States is not a pure free market economy nor is it a purely liberatarian state with minimalist government involvement in peoples pocketbooks and lives....much to the dislike of libertarians I'm sure. <br>
<br>
The United States is also a long ways from being purely socialist or communist like Cuba, where the gov't owns all the factors of production and decides how much of what will be produced. <br>
<br>
We are somewhere in between. We are a mixed free enterprise system in an economic sense. Politically, we are a social democracy where gov't is basically limited in powers but still looks after people from a safety standpoint in its regulatory\policing function and does tax at varying rates to support this function and the social function of providing some basic support for those who cannot support themselves, ie, mentally ill, handicapped, unemployed, poor, elderly, etc. <br>
<br>
Finally, even under the umbrella of &quot;social democracies&quot;...America is just one of many countries with this type of governmental setup. I made the suggestion that you could determinae where we are versus other social democracies by looking at overal taxation burdens for the middle majority of taxpayers. Effective tax rates in social democracies vary anywhere from 40% to 80% in the case of some european countries with higher degrees of socialism.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dmhcas>dmhcas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 118<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/22/03 8:51:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=53.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question for the Libertarians</span><hr size=1> Thank You<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 822<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/22/03 11:10:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=53.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question for the Libertarians</span><hr size=1> I guess my views come from my fundamental views on the role of government and the rights of individuals.<br>
<br>
As I see it, government has no right to forcibly alter the behavior of individuals so long as those individuals are not doing anything that harms others.<br>
<br>
I don't believe that individuals are obligated to put forth effort to help others.  I do believe that they are obligated to not harm others.<br>
<br>
That which you earn/possess is a result of your labors, which come from your energy and your talents, gifts that you were born with and are innately yours.  What you produce with them is innately yours.<br>
<br>
I do believe that people have a right to property, a right to not have their bodies violated (assault/rape/murder/etc), a right to do what they want so long as it does not infringe on the above listed rights of others.  I do not believe that people have a right to eat.  I believe that they must earn the food they eat and if they don't it is not the obligation of any others to provide it.<br>
<br>
This is the distinction for me, sort of a distinction between positive and negative action.  I don't think that you have the right to do anything negative to anyone else, but I don't think that you are obligated to do anything positive for anyone else.<br>
<br>
Thus I think that you are obligated to not hurt anyone else, steal their property, etc.  However I also don't believe you are obligated to feed them, clothe them, educate them, or otherwise use your time, energy, resources, etc for theri benefit.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=raolfcq>RaolfCQ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1066<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/23/03 9:09:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=53.topic&index=15>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question for the Libertarians</span><hr size=1> I don't beleive that rights can be defined individually, because all rights only come from mutual consent.  If only one of us agrees not to hit people, someone will still get hit.  Wether this violates a &quot;right&quot; or not seems to have meaning only in the most abstract sense.  All rights are the result of social negotiation.  I don't hit you because in return you don't hit me, I allow you to accumulate far more than your share of property because I have the potential to do the same, and because I know that I will always have certain basic nessessities.  I think true libertarianism (not that it would ever be implemented because its not something that you would rationally agree to under negotiation) would be overthrown bloodily within 50 years. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 829<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/23/03 12:11:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=53.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question for the Libertarians</span><hr size=1> Again, this is a fundamental point of disagreement, I do not believe that rights are determined by social contract.  Who is right on this one?  No one can say as we have left the realm of logical deduction and gone back to the basic principles that simply must be accepted and from which other things are derived.<br>
<br>
If you were looking at it in terms of mathematics the following pattern is followed:  You assume a set of postulates, you then prove/deduce a set of theorems from those postulates.  The postulates are not proven but rather accepted by all involved.  We aren't agreeing on the postulates here.<br>
<br>
