<br>
Social Contract theory proceeds from the notion that rights &quot;just exist&quot; in a hobbesian &quot;state of nature.&quot; So if by &quot;determined&quot; you mean &quot;given&quot; or &quot;granted&quot; then yes, the contract with gov't and individuals does not provide the initial grant of rights for individuals.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 830<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/23/03 1:26:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=53.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question for the Libertarians</span><hr size=1> Yep, it's really a good thing.  I think that that is the source of our fundamental disagreement.  In summary, you believe rights are granted to individuals by social contract, I believe rights to be innate and to precede social contracts.<br>
<br>
So I guess maybe this is the answer you are looking for as to where the libertarian philosophy comes from.<br>
