<br>
In another sense, it seems like you are just arguing semantics.  &quot;Contract&quot; as a construct of contract law of course has a very specific definition.  That is not the sum of definitions for contract though, and in this case I thought it would be obvious that it just means, &quot;an agreement&quot;.  I don't think there are_ guarentees that the contract will continue to be followed other than people's word and the fact that it is mutually beneficial.  Indeed one of my arguments against pure Libertarianism is that it would result in a social construct that would no longer be beneficial for many, and so would collapse.<br>
<br>
 Im interested how you could define a right to property in particular as existing in a state of nature.  It seems to me that property is entirely a social construct. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=truthreason>TruthReason</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I'm actually Goanad.</span><br>  Posts: 1066<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/23/03 8:11:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=53.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question for the Libertarians</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Im interested how you could define a right to property in particular as existing in a state of nature. It seems to me that property is entirely a social construct. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
In a state of nature of the hobbesian variety Property is very much a &quot;right.&quot; Those who effectively assert property rights absent a state and absent a social contract are those in a position to effectuate through armed action, that they or their group claim deed to a certain peice of property. <br>
<br>
Note that this is NOT an efficient NOR effective system for asserting property rights. Having bands of people roving around grabbing whatever their mass of force and coercion allows them was not viewed in any way as ideal. It's crude, brutish, and like hobbesian life itself, very shortlived in the manner in which confidence regarding property rights was experienced. <br>
<br>
The very fact that the pre-Social Contract assertion of property rights is inefficent fueled the push for the contract itself and reinforces the strength of the same over time. <br>
<br>
<br>
