I do not belong to the Libertarian Party nor will I comment on their platform.  However, I am generally libertarian in leaning in terms of my views of government.<br>
<br>
The basic issue with the social contract is that it needs to be two ways.  That means that it is incumbent upon the citizen to try to contribute and grow.  I know of nobody that does not want to help bridge the unfortunate or help those that are trying.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, many people work very hard not to contribute.  Even you in high school have met people that would rather get high than learn and grow.  Why am I obliged to make there life whole unless they are willing to contribute their part?  After awhile, their avoidance of their obligation of the social contract obviates societies obligations to them.<br>
<br>
When one is younger, it generally the view that this is these people are the exception not the rule.  However, its subtle.  How many are ready to move, emmigrate, change careers, etc. to continue to contribute?<br>
<br>
Until people work to their obligation of the social contract, that contract needs to be limited.  Governments are built to propogate and grow themselves.  Expansion of the roles of government are simply a way to complete this objective.  In most places, this is extension of the social contract.  Thus the libetarian answer is to assume that all governmental expansion is bad, unless it can be proven to be good.<br>
<br>
So, lets take things to an extreme to see where it leads.  Lets say that food becomes part of the social contract.  It then &quot;might&quot; be determined that humans, being omnivores, need meat in their diet.  Then, the government might outlaw vegatarianism as anti-social.  This is clearly an outlandish and extreme scenario.  Its there to make a point and is within the bounds of socialism.<br>
<br>
Cames Houdini<br>
